Based on the 5 line summary output produced by the “summary” R function, we can see that employee MBA attribute does contain some “Missing Values”. This also can confirmed by running the dedicated missing value identificaiton code as shown in the code chunk below. Let’s generate a graphical representation of the “Missing Values” in the given dataset.

I used “mice” R library function algorithm to study the overall pattern of the dataset. Based on the pattern of the data distribution R had filled the missing value as “0”.

The graphical and sum calculation shown above on the treated new dataset confirms the the elimination of NAs.

By studying the classes of all 9 attributes it can be said that “Engineer”, “MBA” and “License” attributes needs to be converted into a factor.

cor(Age,Salary) = 86% cor(Work.Exp,Salary) = 93.2% cor(Age,Work.Exp) = 93% cor(Distance,Salary) = 48% cor(Age,Distance) = 38%

CREATING DUMMY VARIABLES

TRANSPORT :

As we can see that the original dataset predicted variable mode of transport contains of 3 levels of catergorical variables. i.e: 2 Wheelers, Public Transport and Cars

Therfore, another coloumns have been created using “dummy variable” statistical tool to create minimise the number of levels in the predicted variable coloumn. Therefore, a new coloumn called “Transport.cars” have been created with a binary value 1 to represent all the employee who would take the car and “0” for other mode of transport.

levels(Cars_New$Transport)
## NULL
Cars_New_Transform = Cars_New
# Dummy Variable for Transport
Transport.cars=c("Car")
Cars_New_Transform$Transport.cars = ifelse(Cars_New_Transform$Transport %in% Transport.cars,1,0)

# Dummy Variable for Gender
Male=c("Male")
Female=c("Female")

Cars_New_Transform$Male = ifelse(Cars_New_Transform$Gender %in% Male,1,0)
Cars_New_Transform$Female = ifelse(Cars_New_Transform$Gender %in% Female,1,0)


attach(Cars_New_Transform)
## The following objects are masked _by_ .GlobalEnv:
## 
##     Female, Male, Transport.cars
## The following objects are masked from package:BSDA:
## 
##     Engineer, Salary
View(Cars_New_Transform)
class(Cars_New_Transform)
## [1] "data.frame"
Cars_New_Transform$Transport.cars=as.factor(Cars_New_Transform$Transport.cars)

STATISTICAL CONFIRMATIONS ON ASSUMPTIONS:

ASSUMPTION - 1:

Before we proced with any analysis, Normality hypothesis test must be done ensure the Normal Distribution of the variables in the given cars dataset.

The hypothesis for the Normality Test is given below. H0 = The dataset follows a Normal Distribution Against the alternative Hypothesis as, Ha = The dataset does not follow the Normal Distribution properties.

The “Shapiro-Wilk Normality Test” is conducted to investigate the Assumption -1.

There are 4 numeric variables in the dataset. The outcome of the Shapiro-Wilks test on each variable is tabulated below.

VARIABLE p-Value
Age 8.594e-14
Salary 2.2e-16
Work.Exp 2.2e-16
Distance 5.843e-06

All p-values are below 5%, hence the Null Hypothesis is ACCEPTED Scaling must be done to transform the data into a Normal Distribution bell curve inorder to overcome the overfit and underfit problem during the data analysis.

#attach(Cars_New_Transform)
shapiro.test (Age) #Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Age
## W = 0.92321, p-value = 8.594e-14
shapiro.test (Salary) #Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Salary
## W = 0.69305, p-value < 2.2e-16
shapiro.test(Work.Exp)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Work.Exp
## W = 0.8544, p-value < 2.2e-16
shapiro.test(Distance)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  Distance
## W = 0.97805, p-value = 5.843e-06
View(Cars_New_Transform)

ASSUMPTION - 1:

In addition to the above test one more test needs to be conducted to confirm the homogeneity of variance assumption by doing a “Levene Test”.

The Hypothesis testing is done on each variable such as “Age”,“Work.Exp”,“Distance” and “Salary”. Variance on each dataset is checked against the transport classification.

Ho : Variance are equal. Ha : At least one variance is different

leveneTest(Age~Transport.cars,Cars_New_Transform)   # Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance in Age

UNIVARIATE ANALYSIS:

AGE: As you can see the 5 number summary of the treated and prepared dataset that “Age” variable have a mean of 27.33 and median of 27 while the minimum value being 18 and maximum being 43.By theory mean is greater than the median makes the Right Skewed distribution. However the difference between mean and median is not very noticeable. In the histogram plot shown below it can be said “Age” variable observations are normally distributed and there could be some outliers at the upper value of the distribution. Let’s analyze the outliers by doing an “outlier examination”.

hist(Cars_New$Age,col="Green",xlim=c(18,43),
     main="Employee Age Distribution",xlab="Age",breaks = 10)

boxplot(Cars_New$Age,
        horizontal = TRUE,col="blue",main = "Employee Age Distribution", xlab= "Age in Years")

As observed from the “Age” histogram, most number of outliers were observed at the upper side of the age spectrum.This is confirmed by the boxplot diagram. The calculated 26 outliers are listed out below: 38 38 40 36 40 37 39 40 38 36 39 38 40 39 38 42 40 37 43 40 38 37 37 39 36 36

In addition to that there were two repeated outliers were observed at lower end of the distribution spectrum.i.e: 18,18.
